Lac qui Parle Lake is a large, windswept, nutrient rich lake located in west-central Minnesota. The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers manages the lake for flood control purposes. Lac qui Parle's watershed measures over 4,000 square miles. It is comprised primarily of intensively drained agricultural land. This has been to the detriment of Lac qui Parle Lake. Today the lake suffers from algal blooms, turbid water, sedimentation, extreme water level fluctuations, and shoreline erosion. These are the direct result of heavy flows from the watershed that carry large amounts of nutrients and soil. This hasn't always been the case. Lac qui Parle Lake was described in the 1930s as "clean and clear with an abundance of freshwater clams". Unless major land use changes are made in the watershed, it is unlikely that Lac qui Parle Lake will be anything more than a shallow, silt-laden, cattail marsh in a few hundred years. Walleye abundance in Lac qui Parle Lake exceeded what is considered normal for similar lakes in 1998 when 22 walleye were caught per gill net. These fish were from moderate to strong 1995-96 year classes and primarily measured 12-17 inches. Fry were stocked in 1995 and fingerlings in 1996. A fin-clipping study revealed that stocked fingerlings comprised 20% of the 1996 year class, whereas 80% was from natural reproduction. Natural reproduction has, at times, produced large numbers of walleye in Lac qui Parle Lake. However supplemental stockings are probably necessary to maintain a consistent high quality population. Young-of-year walleye are sampled every fall with electrofishing. A poor catch in 1998 suggested that the spring fry stocking had met with very limited success. Electrofishing in 1997 also suggested a weak year class. Considering the unattractive scenario of two consecutively weak walleye year classes, approximately 42,000 walleye fingerlings were stocked during the fall of 1998. These fish received a fin clip and their contribution to the walleye population will be evaluated in 1999 through electrofishing and netting. In 1999 a new walleye stocking program will be initiated at Lac qui Parle Lake. The program is based on the results of a stocking evaluation that has been underway at the lake since 1990. Three million fry will be stocked two of three years under the new program, instead of the previous three year rotation of fry, fingerlings, and no stocking. If neccessary, fingerlings will be stocked as a backup option. The walleye stocking program will continue to be evaluated with annual sampling. Moderate numbers of northern pike were present in 1998 with the majority of them weighing from 2-6 pounds. Northerns were present from the 1994-1998 year classes, an indication of consistent spawning success. Northern pike abundance has been moderate to high since 1991. This has probably been the result of good spring spawning conditions. Lac qui Parle's watershed has some good pike spawning and nursery habitat in the form of seasonally flooded wetlands. Unfortunately, most seasonally flooded wetlands have been drained. The long term sustainability of the northern pike population depends on the protection and restoration of these wetland habitats. Other species that were present in 1998 in decent numbers and sizes included yellow perch, white bass, and black crappie. A large year class of white bass was spawned in 1998. Bullhead numbers remained low, however channel catfish abundance has increased in recent years. Catfish apparently migrated into Lac qui Parle during the high spring water levels in 1997 from the Minnesota River downstream.

Lac qui Parle is a 5,589 acre lake located in west-central Minnesota that is managed by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers as a flood control impoundment. The Department of Natural Resources manages the lake primarily for walleye and northern pike. A 15-inch walleye minimum size regulation was implemented on Lac qui Parle Lake in 1996. Evaluation of this regulation concluded it was not effective in increasing averate size of walleye and may have caused an over-abundance of smaller walleye. Too many small walleye can cause slow growth and increased death rates due to competition for limited forage. The minimum size regulation was abolished in 2005 and replaced by a four fish daily limit, in which one could be 20 inches or larger. The impacts of this new regulation will continue to be monitored with future assessments. Walleye abundance in Lac qui Parle Lake had declined in recent years. As a result of this decline, a combination of adult, fingerling and yearling walleye were stocked in the fall of 2004 and spring of 2005. These stockings appeared to have contributed as the 2005 assessment indicated that walleye abundance had improved substantially. Most sampled walleye ranged from 12-18 inches. High spring water levels in 2005 had allowed for increased production of forage fish, particularly minnow species, and young-of-year sheepshead and white bass. As a result, walleye growth improved. Considering improved growth, anglers can expect good numbers of 14-20 inch walleye to persist in 2006. Northern pike abundance was considered typical for Lac qui Parle Lake. As a result of poor spawning conditions caused by low spring runoff, recent year classes of pike were weak or missing. However, although 2005 was another spring with below average runoff, good reproduction was documented. Construction of a northern pike spawning area was completed in the summer of 2004 and may have contributed to improved reproduction. With the upcoming 2005 year class, anglers can expect an increase in the numbers of 20-23 inch pike in 2006. Channel catfish abundance remained in the upper end of the normal range for Lac qui Parle Lake. Catfish ranged from 11-22 inches, with most measuring 16-19 inches. Shoreline seining sampled numerous young-of-year channel catfish. This was the first substantial catfish reproduction documented in Lac qui Parle Lake. High water levels during June and July appeared to enhance spawning habitat and increased reproductive success. Black and white crappie abundance was in the lower end of the normal range for Lac qui Parle Lake. However, anglers have reported fair success for these species in recent years, particularly in spring and winter. Most crappie sampled in 2005 were quality sized, measuring 10-12 inches. White bass abundance was the highest recorded for Lac qui Parle Lake. However, the majority of sampled bass were young-of-year measuring less than 6 inches. Past assessments indicate that small bass experience high mortality and few survive to age one. The contribution of the 2005 year class will be further evaluated with future assessments. Bluegill and yellow perch were sampled in low abundance, but in numbers consistent with recent assessments. Anglers reported fair success for bluegill in 2005, mainly around the rocks in the southern part of the lake. Most sampled perch were quality sized measuring over 10 inches. Management activies scheduled for Lac qui Parle lake in 2006 include stocking approximately 3 million walleye fry, monitoring of winter dissolved oxygen and fishing pressure, and a fisheries population assessment.

Lac qui Parle Lake (LQP) is located three miles southwest of Milan in western Minnesota. It is an impoundment of the Minnesota River and its water level is controlled by Churchill Dam. LQP is a highly productive lake that measures 5,589 acres and has a maximum depth of 15 feet. Watersheds that ultimately drain into LQP include the Upper Minnesota, Yellow Bank, Lac qui Parle, Pomme de Terre and a portion of the Chippewa. LQP is operated as a flood control reservoir and some years water levels will fluctuate by more than five feet. Depending on the timing and extent of the water level fluctuations, fish may experience good or poor natural reproduction. Some species do well when spring water levels are high, whereas others benefit from lower water levels.

LQP has frequently provided good fishing for walleye. Walleye numbers have been lower than normal since 2006, with the exception of 2011. This has occurred even though high numbers of walleye fry and fingerlings have been stocked. Five walleye were caught per gill net during 2012, which was slightly below LQP's normal range of 7-27. The walleye were primarily from the 2010 and 2011 year classes and were 12-18 inches. Fingerling stocking and natural reproduction have both made substantial contributions to the walleye population based on marking studies. Natural reproduction has produced the two strongest walleye year classes on record (2001 and 2011), however it has been very inconsistent and the population has been supplemented by stocking when appropriate. The 2011 walleye have grown slowly and were only 13.5 inches after three summers. Normal growth would have been 15.5 inches or larger. Slow growth of walleye has occurred at times on Lac qui Parle Lake and is attributed to low forage availability.

Crappie fishing has been good to excellent in recent years. The crappie population increased substantially following the decrease in the walleye population. High numbers of 2010 and 2011 year class crappie were caught during sampling and those fish are expected to provide continued good fishing. Most crappie in 2013 measured 8-11 inches.

High numbers of freshwater drum and white bass have been present at times. Although these are important forage species for walleye, they also compete with them for resources. Anglers are encouraged to harvest drum and white bass. Both species are good to eat, especially if the small amounts of red meat are trimmed from the fillets. Excellent recipes for cooking drum can be found by searching the internet for "drum recipes".

Several additional species were present in numbers worth pursuing. Northern pike were moderately abundant with fish from the 2007-11 year classes present, including fish that exceeded 30 inches. Channel catfish were abundant with many fish over 20 inches. Very limited angling for channel catfish has been observed. Considering their high numbers and large sizes, catfish enthusiasts should consider a trip to Lac qui Parle Lake.

Lac qui Parle (LQP) Lake is a large, shallow, windswept, nutrient rich reservoir located in west-central Minnesota. The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers manages the lake for flood control purposes. Its watershed measures over 4,000 square miles and consists primarily of intensively drained agricultural land. Lac qui Parle Lake suffers from severe algae blooms, high turbidity, sedimentation, shoreline erosion, and extreme water level fluctuations. These are the result of high flows which contain excessive nutrients and sediments entering from the watershed. LQP Lake hasn't always been this way. In the 1930's it was described as clean and clear with an abundance of freshwater clams. Unless major land use changes occur in the watershed, LQP Lake will probably become a shallow, silt-laden cattail marsh within a few hundred years. Although LQP Lake has serious water quality problems, it remains one of Minnesota's premier walleye lakes. Walleye were moderately abundant in 1999, with fish present from ten year classes. Most walleye were from the 1995 and 1996 year classes and measured 14-21 inches. These fish were small for their age and should have measured 16-22 inches. Their poor growth was probably due to a decline in forage during recent years, and a less than ideal 1997 growing season. A 15 inch minimum walleye length limit was implemented on LQP Lake in 1996 as part of a statewide experimental regulations study. Its objectives are to increase the average length of walleye harvested by anglers, and to increase the number of larger walleye in the lake. The regulation will be evaluated through 2002, and depending upon its effectiveness it will remain in effect, be changed, or abolished. Walleye stocking is an important management tool at LQP Lake. Several studies have shown that fry stocking, natural reproduction, and under certain conditions, fingerling stocking can all contribute substantially to the walleye population. Fry are routinely stocked two of three years. If annual assessments reveal a need, fingerlings may also be stocked. Natural reproduction can produce large numbers of young walleye during springs with suitable spawning conditions. Moderate numbers of northern pike, crappie, white bass, and channel catfish were present in 1999. The pike population has declined considerably since the mid 1990's, probably due to poor spawning conditions during the last few years. Ideal pike spawning areas are seasonally flooded, grassy wetlands that hold spring run-off for at least a month. Unfortunately, most of these in the LQP Lake watershed have been drained. The long term sustainability of the northern pike population depends on the protection and restoration of these wetland habitats. Channel catfish abundance increased considerably during 1997 when they migrated into the lake from the Minnesota River during the "great flood". Anglers caught numerous channel catfish just upstream from LQP Lake at the Marsh Lake spillway during the summer. A new public access was installed on the upper basin of LQP Lake at Hanthos Beach in 1999, and 1900 feet of shoreline at the site were stabilized with riprap. These were cooperative projects completed by Eagle Scout Noah Borstad, the LQP Lake Association, the LQP Watershed Project Association, the Appleton Sportsmens Club, Chippewa County Pheasants Forever, MinnKota Sportsmens Club, LQP County Pheasants Forever, LQP County, LQP SWCD, and the MN DNR. Future management activities will include annual assessments, stocking as needed, and work within the watershed to help improve the water quality of the lake and its associated streams.

Lac qui Parle Lake is a large (5,589 acres) class 41 lake in west central Minnesota located in Lac qui Parle, Chippewa, and Swift Counties. It is an impoundment of the Minnesota River, which is its major inlet and outlet. The lake is primarily managed for walleye and northern pike, but also provides fishing opportunities for white bass, crappie, and channel catfish.

Anglers can expect walleye fishing to be difficult on Lac qui Parle. Walleye abundance in 2008 was at its lowest level ever recorded. Those walleye that are caught are going to average 14.6 inches long and 1.3 lbs. Walleye fishing is likely going to improve, as two abundant year classes (2007 and 2008) continue to grow and provide opportunities for anglers.

Black crappie continue to provide excellent opportunities for anglers. This is due to an abundant 2005 year class of fish. Anglers can expect to see black crappie 10.2 inches and 0.7 lb. Unfortunately, the black crappie population will likely decline over the next few years due to limited numbers of younger fish.

Although abundance has declined slightly from 2007, fishermen can still expect to see northern pike show up in their catches. The northern pike that were sampled in 2008 had an average size of 3.2 lbs. and 22.3 inches. Pike abundance will likely remain stable as several young of year fish were sampled in 2008.

White bass abundance was at its lowest level since 2004. Most of the fish were three-years-old and had an average size of 10 inches and 0.6 lb. Catfish anglers should be pleased with Lac qui Parle. Channel catfish are at their highest abundance ever recorded. Catfish up to 28 inches long were sampled, but 67% were 12-15 inches long.

Other game fish species sampled in low abundance were bluegill and yellow perch. Freshwater drum abundance from 2007, 82% being eleven inches or less. Other common non-game fish sampled were black bullhead, common carp, white sucker, and redhorse.

Future management activities planned for Lac qui Parle include monitoring of winter dissolved oxygen levels and fishing pressure, fish stocking as needed, fall population assessments and electrofishing for young-of-year walleye.

Lac qui Parle Lake (LQP) is located three miles southwest of Milan in western Minnesota. It is a 5,589 acre impoundment of the Minnesota River with a maximum depth of 15 feet. Its water level is controlled by Churchill Dam which is located ? mile downstream on the Minnesota River. Watersheds that drain into LQP include the Upper Minnesota, Yellow Bank, Lac qui Parle, Pomme de Terre and a portion of the Chippewa. LQP is operated as a flood control reservoir and some years water levels will fluctuate by more than five feet. Depending on the timing and extent of the water level fluctuations, fish may experience good to poor natural reproduction.
This 2019 survey was conducted to collect routine fish population data using gill nets, shoreline seining and fall night electrofishing. These data can be compared to historical standard and targeted survey data from LQP.

LQP often provides good Walleye fishing. The Walleye population has resulted from natural reproduction, stocking and migration from upstream water bodies. Walleye numbers have remained relatively stable over the last several years. Fourteen Walleyes were caught per gill net in 2019, indicating a moderate population. Walleyes were present from a wide range of sizes. The 2017 year class comprised 51% of the sample and they averaged 16 inches. Walleyes have grown slower than expected at times, especially young Walleyes, likely due to limited food. LQP becomes extremely turbid during strong winds due to sediment suspension. This limits the ability of important food organisms to reproduce and grow, especially beneficial algae, zooplankton and small fish. In addition, the highly variable water levels affect the ability of many fish species to successfully spawn. These factors impact the production of food items that are important for successful growth and recruitment of Walleyes.

Crappie fishing has been very good for many years. The crappie population has typically been higher when the Walleye population has been lower. Crappies were abundant in the 2019 survey and many were 11-13 inches. Smaller crappies were also abundant which should keep the population healthy into the future.

Northern Pike were moderately abundant from a wide range of sizes, including large pike up to 38 inches. Anglers and spearers have reported good pike fishing during recent years. Pike have experienced relatively consistent natural reproduction regardless of spring water levels. It's likely they have been finding suitable spawning habitat along the north end of the lake where wetlands have been formed by beaver dams, or along the edges of emergent vegetation. LQP is in the southern Northern Pike zone where the possession limit is two fish with a minimum size limit of 24 inches. See the Minnesota Fishing Regulations booklet for more details.

High numbers of Freshwater Drum were present. Small drum are important food for many species of fish, however large drum compete with game fish for resources. Anglers are encouraged to harvest drum. They are good to eat, especially if the small amounts of red meat are trimmed from the fillets. Excellent recipes for cooking drum can be found on the internet by searching "drum recipes". Drum are an excellent choice for a fish fry because there is no possession limit.

Channel Catfish were abundant from a wide range of sizes. Very little angling for catfish has been known to occur. Considering their high numbers and large sizes, catfish enthusiasts should consider a trip to LQP.

Management activities for LQP include annual fish surveys, Walleye stocking, monitoring winter dissolved oxygen and ice-house counts. Zebra mussels were found to be present in 2016. Anglers are reminded to drain all water from boats, motors, compartments and containers before leaving the lake, and to keep drain plugs out while transporting watercraft.
